  "nursesNote": "The therapeutic nurse-patient relationship moves through phases. In pre-orientation the nurse gathers information and examines personal feelings before meeting the patient. In orientation the nurse builds trust and rapport, sets goals and boundaries, and explains confidentiality and its limits. In the working phase the nurse helps the patient identify and explore problems, express feelings, and make changes. In termination the nurse summarizes, evaluates whether goals were met, and prepares for the ending; planning for termination begins early and feelings of loss are addressed. Throughout, the nurse keeps clear professional boundaries: the relationship is goal-directed and patient-focused, not a friendship, with limited self-disclosure and no gifts or social contact, while staying aware of transference and countertransference.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Prepare and self-reflect before meeting the patient",
    "Build trust and set goals and boundaries in orientation",
    "Explore problems and promote change in the working phase",
    "Summarize and plan for termination early",
    "Maintain professional boundaries throughout"
  ],
